# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: reqwest-rust
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] The **client–server model** is a form of messaging pattern in a distributed application structure that partitions tasks or workloads between the providers of a resource or service, called servers, and service requesters, called clients.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Often clients and servers communicate over a computer network on separate hardware, but both client and server may be on the same device.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] A server host runs one or more server programs, which share their resources with clients.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] A client usually does not share its computing resources, but it requests content or service from a server and may share its own content as part of the request.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Clients, therefore, initiate communication sessions with servers, which await incoming requests.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Examples of computer applications that use the client–server model are email, network printing, and the World Wide Web.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] The server component provides a function or service to one or many clients, which initiate requests for such services.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Servers are classified by the services they provide.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] For example, a web server serves web pages and a file server serves computer files.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] A shared resource may be any of the server computer's software and electronic components, from programs and data to processors and storage devices.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] The sharing of resources of a server constitutes a *service*.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Whether a computer is a client, a server, or both, is determined by the nature of the application that requires the service functions.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] For example, a single computer can run a web server and file server software at the same time to serve different data to clients making different kinds of requests.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] The client software can also communicate with server software within the same computer.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Communication between servers, such as to synchronize data, is sometimes called *inter-server* or *server-to-server* communication.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Generally, a service is an abstraction of computer resources and a client does not have to be concerned with how the server performs while fulfilling the request and delivering the response.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] The client only has to understand the response based on the relevant application protocol, i.e. the content and the formatting of the data for the requested service.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Clients and servers exchange messages in a request–response messaging pattern.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] The client sends a request, and the server returns a response.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] This exchange of messages is an example of inter-process communication.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] To communicate, the computers must have a common language, and they must follow rules so that both the client and the server know what to expect.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] The language and rules of communication are defined in a communications protocol.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] All protocols operate in the application layer.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] The application layer protocol defines the basic patterns of the dialogue.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] To formalize the data exchange even further, the server may implement an application programming interface (API).
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] The API is an abstraction layer for accessing a service.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] By restricting communication to a specific content format, it facilitates parsing.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] By abstracting access, it facilitates cross-platform data exchange.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] A server may receive requests from many distinct clients in a short period.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] A computer can only perform a limited number of tasks at any moment, and relies on a scheduling system to prioritize incoming requests from clients to accommodate them.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] To prevent abuse and maximize availability, the server software may limit the availability to clients.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Denial of service attacks are designed to exploit a server's obligation to process requests by overloading it with excessive request rates.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Encryption should be applied if sensitive information is to be communicated between the client and the server.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] When a bank customer accesses online banking services with a web browser (the client), the client initiates a request to the bank's web server.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] The customer's login credentials are compared against a database, and the webserver accesses that database server as a client.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] An application server interprets the returned data by applying the bank's business logic and provides the output to the webserver.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Finally, the webserver returns the result to the client web browser for display.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] In each step of this sequence of client–server message exchanges, a computer processes a request and returns data.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] This is the request-response messaging pattern.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] When all the requests are met, the sequence is complete.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] This example illustrates a design pattern applicable to the client–server model: separation of concerns.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Server-side refers to programs and operations that run on the server.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] This is in contrast to client-side programs and operations which run on the client.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] "Server-side software" refers to a computer application, such as a web server, that runs on remote server hardware, reachable from a user's local computer, smartphone, or other device.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Operations may be performed server-side because they require access to information or functionality that is not available on the client, or because performing such operations on the client side would be slow, unreliable, or insecure.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Client and server programs may be commonly available ones such as free or commercial web servers and web browsers, communicating with each other using standardized protocols.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Or, programmers may write their own server, client, and communications protocol which can only be used with one another.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Server-side operations include both those that are carried out in response to client requests, and non-client-oriented operations such as maintenance tasks.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] In a computer security context, server-side vulnerabilities or attacks refer to those that occur on a server computer system, rather than on the client side, or in between the two.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] For example, an attacker might exploit an SQL injection vulnerability in a web application in order to maliciously change or gain unauthorized access to data in the server's database.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Alternatively, an attacker might break into a server system using vulnerabilities in the underlying operating system and then be able to access database and other files in the same manner as authorized administrators of the server.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] In the case of an Internet-dependent user application like Google Earth, while querying and display of map data takes place on the client side, the server is responsible for permanent storage of map data, resolving user queries into map data to be returned to the client, etc.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Web applications and services can be implemented in almost any language, as long as they can return data to standards-based web browsers (possibly via intermediary programs) in formats which they can use.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Client-side refers to operations that are performed by the client in a computer network.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Typically, a client is a computer application, such as a web browser, that runs on a user's local computer, smartphone, or other device, and connects to a server as necessary.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Additionally, if operations can be performed by the client, without sending data over the network, they may take less time, use less bandwidth, and incur a lesser security risk.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] When the server serves data in a commonly used manner, for example according to standard protocols such as HTTP or FTP, users may have their choice of a number of client programs (e.g. most modern web browsers can request and receive data using both HTTP and FTP).
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] In the case of more specialized applications, programmers may write their own server, client, and communications protocol which can only be used with one another.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Programs that run on a user's local computer without ever sending or receiving data over a network are not considered clients, and so the operations of such programs would not be termed client-side operations.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] In a computer security context, client-side vulnerabilities or attacks refer to those that occur on the client / user's computer system, rather than on the server side, or in between the two.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] As an example, if a server contained an encrypted file or message which could only be decrypted using a key housed on the user's computer system, a client-side attack would normally be an attacker's only opportunity to gain access to the decrypted contents.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] For instance, the attacker might cause malware to be installed on the client system, allowing the attacker to view the user's screen, record the user's keystrokes, and steal copies of the user's encryption keys, etc.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Alternatively, an attacker might employ cross-site scripting vulnerabilities to execute malicious code on the client's system without needing to install any permanently resident malware.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Distributed computing projects such as SETI@home and the Great Internet Mersenne Prime Search, as well as Internet-dependent applications like Google Earth, rely primarily on client-side operations.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] They initiate a connection with the server (either in response to a user query, as with Google Earth, or in an automated fashion, as with SETI@home), and request some data.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] The server selects a data set (a server-side operation) and sends it back to the client.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] The client then analyzes the data (a client-side operation), and, when the analysis is complete, displays it to the user (as with Google Earth) and/or transmits the results of calculations back to the server (as with SETI@home).
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] An early form of client–server architecture is remote job entry, dating at least to OS/360 (announced 1964), where the request was to run a job, and the response was the output.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] While formulating the client–server model in the 1960s and 1970s, computer scientists building ARPANET (at the Stanford Research Institute) used the terms *server-host* (or *serving host*) and *user-host* (or *using-host*), and these appear in the early documents RFC 5 and RFC 4.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] This usage was continued at Xerox PARC in the mid-1970s.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] One context in which researchers used these terms was in the design of a computer network programming language called Decode-Encode Language (DEL).
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] The purpose of this language was to accept commands from one computer (the user-host), which would return status reports to the user as it encoded the commands in network packets.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Another DEL-capable computer, the server-host, received the packets, decoded them, and returned formatted data to the user-host.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] A DEL program on the user-host received the results to present to the user.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Development of DEL was just beginning in 1969, the year that the United States Department of Defense established ARPANET (predecessor of Internet).
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] An early use of the word *client* occurs in "Separating Data from Function in a Distributed File System", a 1978 paper by Xerox PARC computer scientists Howard Sturgis, James Mitchell, and Jay Israel.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] The authors are careful to define the term for readers, and explain that they use it to distinguish between the user and the user's network node (the client).
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] By 1992, the word *server* had entered into general parlance.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] The client-server model does not dictate that server-hosts must have more resources than client-hosts.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Rather, it enables any general-purpose computer to extend its capabilities by using the shared resources of other hosts.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Centralized computing, however, specifically allocates a large number of resources to a small number of computers.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] The more computation is offloaded from client-hosts to the central computers, the simpler the client-hosts can be.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] It relies heavily on network resources (servers and infrastructure) for computation and storage.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] A diskless node loads even its operating system from the network, and a computer terminal has no operating system at all; it is only an input/output interface to the server.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] In contrast, a rich client, such as a personal computer, has many resources and does not rely on a server for essential functions.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] As microcomputers decreased in price and increased in power from the 1980s to the late 1990s, many organizations transitioned computation from centralized servers, such as mainframes and minicomputers, to rich clients.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] This afforded greater, more individualized dominion over computer resources, but complicated information technology management.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] During the 2000s, web applications matured enough to rival application software developed for a specific microarchitecture.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] This maturation, more affordable mass storage, and the advent of service-oriented architecture were among the factors that gave rise to the cloud computing trend of the 2010s.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] In addition to the client-server model, distributed computing applications often use the peer-to-peer (P2P) application architecture.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] In the client-server model, the server is often designed to operate as a centralized system that serves many clients.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] The computing power, memory and storage requirements of a server must be scaled appropriately to the expected workload.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Load-balancing and failover systems are often employed to scale the server beyond a single physical machine.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Load balancing is defined as the methodical and efficient distribution of network or application traffic across multiple servers in a server farm.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Each load balancer sits between client devices and backend servers, receiving and then distributing incoming requests to any available server capable of fulfilling them.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] In a peer-to-peer network, two or more computers (*peers*) pool their resources and communicate in a decentralized system.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Peers are coequal, or equipotent nodes in a non-hierarchical network.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Unlike clients in a client-server or client-queue-client network, peers communicate with each other directly.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] In peer-to-peer networking, an algorithm in the peer-to-peer communications protocol balances load, and even peers with modest resources can help to share the load.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] If a node becomes unavailable, its shared resources remain available as long as other peers offer it.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Ideally, a peer does not need to achieve high availability because other, redundant peers make up for any resource downtime; as the availability and load capacity of peers change, the protocol reroutes requests.
[src:reqwest-rust/client-server-model] Both client-server and master-slave are regarded as sub-categories of distributed peer-to-peer systems.
[src:reqwest-rust/http-client] On the Web, a **user agent** is a software agent responsible for retrieving and facilitating end-user interaction with Web content.
[src:reqwest-rust/http-client] This includes all web browsers, such as Google Chrome and Safari, some email clients, standalone download managers like youtube-dl, and other command-line utilities like cURL.
[src:reqwest-rust/http-client] The user agent is the client in a client–server system.
[src:reqwest-rust/http-client] The HTTP User-Agent header is intended to clearly identify the agent to the server.
[src:reqwest-rust/http-client] However, this header can be omitted or spoofed, so some websites use other detection methods.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a request–response protocol in the client–server model.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A transaction starts with a client submitting a request to the server, the server attempts to satisfy the request and returns a response to the client that describes the disposition of the request and optionally contains a requested resource such as an HTML document or other content.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In a common scenario, a web browser acts as the client, and a web server, hosting one or more websites, is the server.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web browser is an example of a user agent (UA).
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Other types of user agent include the indexing software used by search providers (web crawlers), voice browsers, mobile apps, and other software that accesses, consumes, or displays web content.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is designed to permit intermediate network elements to improve or enable communications between clients and servers.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] High-traffic websites often benefit from web cache servers that deliver content on behalf of upstream servers to improve response time.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Web browsers cache previously accessed web resources and reuse them, whenever possible, to reduce network traffic.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP proxy servers at private network boundaries can facilitate communication for clients without a globally routable address, by relaying messages with external servers.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To allow intermediate HTTP nodes (proxy servers, web caches, etc.) to accomplish their functions, some of the HTTP headers (found in HTTP requests/responses) are managed hop-by-hop whereas other HTTP headers are managed end-to-end (managed only by the source client and by the target web server).
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web resource is located by a uniform resource locator (URL), using the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes *http* and *https*.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] URIs are encoded as hyperlinks in HTML documents, so as to form interlinked hypertext documents.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol has been revised over time.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A version is identified as HTTP/# where # is the version number.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This article covers aspects of all versions but provides primary coverage for HTTP/0.9, HTTP/1.0, and HTTP/1.1.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Separate articles cover HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 in detail.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, a separate TCP connection to the same server is made for every resource request.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, instead a TCP connection can be reused to make multiple resource requests (i.e. of HTML pages, frames, images, scripts, stylesheets, etc.).
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 communications therefore experience less latency as the establishment of TCP connections presents considerable overhead, especially under high traffic conditions.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Enhancements added with HTTP/2 allow for less latency and, in most cases, higher speeds than HTTP/1.1 communications.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC + UDP transport protocols instead of TCP.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Only the IP layer is used (which UDP, like TCP, builds on).
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This slightly improves the average speed of communications and avoids the occasional problem of TCP connection congestion that can temporarily block or slow down the data flow of all its streams (another form of "*head of line blocking*").
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 is supported by 71% of websites (34.1% HTTP/2 + 36.9% HTTP/3 with backwards compatibility) and supported by almost all web browsers (over 98% of users).
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is also supported by major web servers over Transport Layer Security (TLS) using an Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 is used on 36.9% of websites and is supported by most web browsers, i.e.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] (at least partially) supported by 97% of users.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC instead of TCP for the underlying transport protocol.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Like HTTP/2, it does not obsolete previous major versions of the protocol.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2019, support for HTTP/3 was first added to Cloudflare and Chrome and also enabled in Firefox.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 has lower latency for real-world web pages and loads faster than HTTP/2, in some cases over three times faster than HTTP/1.1, which is still commonly the only protocol enabled.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTPS, the secure variant of HTTP, is used by more than 85% of websites.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP presumes an underlying and reliable transport layer protocol.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard choice of the underlying protocol prior to HTTP/3 is Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses a different transport layer called QUIC, which provides reliability on top of the unreliable User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 and earlier have been adapted to be used over plain unreliable UDP in multicast and unicast situations, forming HTTPMU and HTTPU.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They are used in UPnP and Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP), two protocols usually run on a local area network.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a stateless application-level protocol and it requires a reliable network transport connection to exchange data between client and server.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP implementations, TCP/IP connections are used using well-known ports (typically port 80 if the connection is unencrypted or port 443 if the connection is encrypted, see also List of TCP and UDP port numbers).
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/2, a TCP/IP connection plus multiple protocol channels are used.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/3, the application transport protocol QUIC over UDP is used.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Data is exchanged through a sequence of request–response messages which are exchanged by a session layer transport connection.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP client initially tries to establish a connection, real or virtual, with a server.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP server listening on the port accepts the connection and then waits for a client's request message.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The client sends its HTTP request message.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Upon receiving the request the server sends back an HTTP response message, which includes header(s) plus a body if it is required.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The body of this response message is typically the requested resource, although an error message or other information may also be returned.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At any time and for many reasons, either the client or server can close the connection.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Closing a connection is usually advertised by one or more HTTP headers in the last request or response.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, the TCP/IP connection is always closed after server response has been sent, so it is never persistent.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, the TCP/IP connection should always be closed by server after a response has been sent.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, a keep-alive-mechanism was officially introduced so that a connection could be reused for more than one request/response.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such persistent connections reduce request latency perceptibly because the client does not need to re-negotiate the TCP 3-Way-Handshake connection after the first request has been sent.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Another positive side effect is that, in general, the connection becomes faster with time due to TCP's slow-start-mechanism.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 added also HTTP pipelining in order to further reduce lag time when using persistent connections by allowing clients to send multiple requests before waiting for each response.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Because of this, only HEAD and some GET requests (i.e. limited to real file requests and so with URLs without query string used as a command, etc.) could be pipelined in a safe and idempotent mode.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] After many years of struggling with the problems introduced by enabling pipelining, this feature was first disabled and then removed from most browsers.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Pipelining was also removed because of the announced adoption of HTTP/2.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 extended the usage of persistent connections by multiplexing many concurrent requests/responses through a single TCP/IP connection.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 does not use TCP/IP connections but QUIC + UDP.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, a requested resource was always sent in its entirety.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 added headers to manage resources cached by a client in order to allow conditional GET requests.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As a stateless protocol, HTTP does not require the web server to retain information or status about each user for the duration of multiple requests.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a web application needs an application session, it implements it via HTTP cookies, hidden variables in a web form or another mechanism.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Typically, to start a session, an interactive login is performed, and to end a session, a logout is requested by the user.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] These kind of operations use a custom authentication mechanism, not HTTP authentication.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides multiple authentication schemes such as basic access authentication and digest access authentication which operate via a challenge–response mechanism whereby the server identifies and issues a challenge before serving the requested content.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides a general framework for access control and authentication, via an extensible set of challenge–response authentication schemes, which can be used by a server to challenge a client request and by a client to provide authentication information.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The authentication mechanisms described above belong to the HTTP protocol and are managed by client and server HTTP software (if configured to require authentication before allowing client access to one or more web resources), and not by the web applications using an application session.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP authentication specification includes realms that provide an arbitrary, implementation-specific construct for further dividing resources common to a given root URI.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The realm value string, if present, is combined with the canonical root URI to form the protection space component of the challenge.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This in effect allows the server to define separate authentication scopes under one root URI.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The most popular way of establishing an encrypted HTTP connection is HTTPS.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Two other methods for establishing an encrypted HTTP connection also exist: Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol, and using the HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header to specify an upgrade to TLS.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Browser support for these two is, however, nearly non-existent.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This section describes messages for HTTP/1.1.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Later versions, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, use a binary protocol, where headers are encoded in a single `HEADERS` and zero or more `CONTINUATION` frames using HPACK (HTTP/2) or QPACK (HTTP/3), which both provide efficient header compression.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request or response line from HTTP/1 has also been replaced by several pseudo-header fields, each beginning with a colon (`:`).
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At the highest level, a message consists of a header followed by a body.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header consists of lines of ASCII text; each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Structured data that differs for request vs. response.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] lines (at least 1 for HTTP/1.1); see below.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body consists of data in any format; not limited to ASCII.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The format must match that specified by the `Content-Type` header field if the message contains one.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body is optional or, in other words, can be blank.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Before HTTP/2, the term *entity* was used to mean the body plus header fields that describe the body.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In particular, not all headers were considered part of the entity.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The term *entity header* referred to a header that was considered part of the entity, and sometimes the body was called the *entity body*.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Modern documentation uses *body* and *header* without using *entity*.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field represents metadata about the containing message.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, the information of a header field is used by software and not shown to the user.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field line is formatted as a name-value pair with a colon separator.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Whitespace is not allowed around the name, but leading and trailing whitespace is ignored for the value part.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Unlike a method name that must match exactly (case-sensitive), a header field name is matched ignoring case although often shown with each word capitalized.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the following are header fields for `Host` and `Accept-Language`.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standards do not limit the size of a header field or the number of fields in a message.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, most servers, clients, and proxy software impose limits for practical and security reasons.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the Apache 2.3 server by default limits the size of each field to 8190 bytes, and there can be at most 100 header fields in a single request.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although deprecated by RFC 7230, in the past, long lines could be split into multiple lines with a continuation line starting with a space or tab character.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request is sent by a client to a server.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line includes a method name, a request URI and the protocol version with a single space between each field.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request header fields allow the client to pass additional information beyond the request line, acting as request modifiers (similarly to the parameters of a procedure).
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the client, about the target resource, or about the expected handling of the request.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the HTTP/1.1 protocol, all header fields except `Host` are optional.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request line containing only the path name is accepted by servers to maintain compatibility with HTTP clients before the HTTP/1.0 specification in RFC 1945.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol structures transaction as operating on resources.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] What a resource represents, whether pre-existing data or data that is generated dynamically, depends on the implementation of the server.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Often, the resource corresponds to a file or the output of an executable running on the server.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request identifies a method (sometimes informally called *verb*) to classify the desired action to be performed on a resource.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.0 specification defined the GET, HEAD, and POST methods as well as listing the PUT, DELETE, LINK and UNLINK methods under additional methods.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, the HTTP/1.1 specification added five new methods: PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, and TRACE.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Any client can use any method and the server can be configured to support any combination of methods.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a method is unknown to an intermediate, it will be treated as an unsafe and non-idempotent method.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] There is no limit to the number of methods that can be defined, which allows for future methods to be specified without breaking existing infrastructure.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, WebDAV defined seven new methods and RFC 5789 specified the PATCH method.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A general-purpose web server is required to implement at least GET and HEAD, and all other methods are considered optional by the specification.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is in contrast to HTTP header field names which are case-insensitive.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is for a representation of a resource.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] include the representation data in the body.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] in the response header, without having to transfer the entire representation.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to process a resource in some way.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to create or update a resource with the state in the request.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A distinction from POST is that the client specifies the target location on the server.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] to the origin server identified by the request target.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request is for a report of the HTTP methods that are supported for a resource.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This can be used to check the functionality of a web server by requesting '*' instead of a specific resource.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Requests the server to respond with the received request in the response body.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That way a client can see what (if any) changes or additions have been made by intermediaries.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to modify a resource according to its partial state in the request.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Compared to PUT, this can save bandwidth by sending only part of a resource's representation instead of all of it.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *safe* if a request with that method has no intended effect on the server.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are defined as safe.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In other words, safe methods are intended to be read-only.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods can still have side effects not seen by the client, such as appending request information to a log file or charging an advertising account.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, and PATCH are not safe.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They may modify the state of the server or have other effects such as sending an email.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such methods are therefore not usually used by conforming web robots or web crawlers; some that do not conform tend to make requests without regard to context or consequences.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Despite the prescribed safety of GET requests, in practice their handling by the server is not technically limited in any way.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Careless or deliberately irregular programming can allow GET requests to cause non-trivial changes on the server.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is discouraged because of the problems which can occur when web caching, search engines, and other automated agents make unintended changes on the server.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, a website might allow deletion of a resource through a URL such as *https://example.com/article/1234/delete*, which, if arbitrarily fetched, even using GET, would simply delete the article.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A properly coded website would require a DELETE or POST method for this action, which non-malicious bots would not make.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] One example of this occurring in practice was during the short-lived Google Web Accelerator beta, which prefetched arbitrary URLs on the page a user was viewing, causing records to be automatically altered or deleted *en masse*.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The beta was suspended only weeks after its first release, following widespread criticism.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *idempotent* if multiple identical requests with that method have the same effect as a single such request.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods PUT and DELETE, and safe methods are defined as idempotent.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods are trivially idempotent, since they are intended to have no effect on the server whatsoever; the PUT and DELETE methods, meanwhile, are idempotent since successive identical requests will be ignored.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A website might, for instance, set up a PUT endpoint to modify a user's recorded email address.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If this endpoint is configured correctly, any requests which ask to change a user's email address to the same email address which is already recorded—e.g. duplicate requests following a successful request—will have no effect.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Similarly, a request to DELETE a certain user will have no effect if that user has already been deleted.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, CONNECT, and PATCH are not necessarily idempotent, and therefore sending an identical POST request multiple times may further modify the state of the server or have further effects, such as sending multiple emails.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In some cases this is the desired effect, but in other cases it may occur accidentally.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A user might, for example, inadvertently send multiple POST requests by clicking a button again if they were not given clear feedback that the first click was being processed.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While web browsers may show alert dialog boxes to warn users in some cases where reloading a page may re-submit a POST request, it is generally up to the web application to handle cases where a POST request should not be submitted more than once.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Note that whether or not a method is idempotent is not enforced by the protocol or web server.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is perfectly possible to write a web application in which (for example) a database insert or other non-idempotent action is triggered by a GET or other request.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To do so against recommendations, however, may result in undesirable consequences, if a user agent assumes that repeating the same request is safe when it is not.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *cacheable* if responses to requests with that method may be stored for future reuse.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, and POST are defined as cacheable.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, TRACE, and PATCH are not cacheable.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A response is sent to the client by the server.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line of a response consists of the protocol version, a status code and optionally a reason phrase with fields separated by a single space character.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following response start line specifies protocol version `HTTP/1.1`, status code `400` and reason phrase `Bad Request`.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Response header fields allow the server to pass additional information beyond the status line, acting as response modifiers.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the server or about further access to the target resource or related resources.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Each response header field has a defined meaning which can be further refined by the semantics of the request method or response status code.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The status code is a three-digit, decimal, integer value that represents the disposition of the server's attempt to satisfy the client's request.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, a client handles a response primarily based on the status code and secondarily on response header fields.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A client may not understand each status code that a server reports but it must understand the class as indicated by the first digit and treat an unrecognized code as equivalent to the x00 code of that class.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was received, continuing process.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was successfully received, understood, and accepted.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Further action needs to be taken in order to complete the request.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request cannot be fulfilled due to an issue that the client might be able to control.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The server failed to fulfill an apparently valid request.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard reason phrases are only recommendations.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web server is allowed to use a localized equivalent.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a status code indicates a problem, the user agent might display the reason phrase to the user to provide further information about the nature of the problem.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard also allows the user agent to attempt to interpret the reason phrase, though this might be unwise since the standard explicitly specifies that status codes are machine-readable and reason phrases are human-readable.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following demonstrates an HTTP/1.1 request-response transaction for a server at www.example.com, port 80.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 would use the same messages except for a few missing headers.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 would use the same request-response mechanism but with different representations for HTTP headers.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following is a request with no body.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It consists of a start line, 6 header fields and a blank line – each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Host` header field distinguishes between various DNS names sharing a single IP address, allowing name-based virtual hosting.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While optional in HTTP/1.0, it is mandatory in HTTP/1.1.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although not clear in the representation above (due to limitations of this wiki), the blank line at the end results in ending in two line terminator sequences.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Represented as a stream of characters, a shorted version of above shows this more clearly with `<CRLF>` representing a line terminator sequence: `GET / HTTP/1.1<CRLF>Host: www.example.com<CRLF><CRLF>`.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the following response, the ETag (entity tag) header field is used to determine if a cached version of the requested resource is identical to the current version of the resource on the server.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Content-Type` header field specifies the Internet media type of the data conveyed by the HTTP message, and `Content-Length` indicates its length in bytes.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.1 webserver publishes its ability to respond to requests for a byte range of the resource by including `Accept-Ranges: bytes`.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is useful, if the client needs to have only certain portions of a resource sent by the server, which is called byte serving.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When `Connection: close` is sent, it means that the web server will close the TCP connection immediately after the end of the transfer of this response.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Most of the header fields are optional but some are mandatory.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When header `Content-Length` is missing from a response with a body, then this should be considered an error in HTTP/1.0 but it may not be an error in HTTP/1.1 if header `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` is present.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Chunked transfer encoding uses a chunk size of 0 to mark the end of the content.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some old implementations of HTTP/1.0 omitted the header `Content-Length` when the length of the body was not known at the beginning of the response and so the transfer of data to client continued until server closed the socket.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] `Content-Encoding: gzip` informs the client that the body is compressed per the gzip algorithm.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A content delivery protocol that was displaced by HTTP in the early 1990s.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A Gopher-inspired protocol which mandates privacy-related features.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Tim Berners-Lee and his team at CERN are credited with inventing HTTP, along with HTML and the associated technology for a web server and a client user interface called web browser.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Berners-Lee designed HTTP in order to help with the adoption of his other idea: the "WorldWideWeb" project, which was first proposed in 1989, now known as the World Wide Web.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of HTTP was initiated in 1989 and summarized in a simple document describing the behavior of a client and a server using the first HTTP version, named 0.9.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That version was subsequently developed, eventually becoming the public 1.0.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of early HTTP Request for Comments (RFC) documents started a few years later in a coordinated effort by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), with work later moving to the IETF.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol used had only one method, namely GET, which would request a page from a server.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The response from the server was always an HTML page.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since 1992, a new document was written to specify the evolution of the basic protocol towards its next full version.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It supported both the simple request method of the 0.9 version and the full GET request that included the client HTTP version.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This was the first of the many unofficial HTTP/1.0 drafts that preceded the final work on HTTP/1.0.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned to revise and publish new versions of the protocol as HTTP/1.0 and HTTP/1.1 within 1995, but, because of the many revisions, that timeline lasted much more than one year.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned also to specify a far future version of HTTP called HTTP-NG (HTTP Next Generation) that would have solved all remaining problems, of previous versions, related to performances, low latency responses, etc. but this work started only a few years later and it was never completed.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 1996, RFC 1945 was published as a final HTTP/1.0 revision of what had been used in previous 4 years as a pre-standard HTTP/1.0-draft which was already used by many web browsers and web servers.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In early 1996 developers started to even include unofficial extensions of the HTTP/1.0 protocol (i.e. keep-alive connections, etc.) into their products by using drafts of the upcoming HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since early 1996, major web browsers and web server developers also started to implement new features specified by pre-standard HTTP/1.1 drafts specifications.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] End-user adoption of the new versions of browsers and servers was rapid.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In March 1996, one web hosting company reported that over 40% of browsers in use on the Internet used the new HTTP/1.1 header "Host" to enable virtual hosting, and that by June 1996, 65% of all browsers accessing their servers were pre-standard HTTP/1.1 compliant.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In January 1997, RFC 2068 was officially released as HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 1999, RFC 2616 was released to include all improvements and updates based on previous (obsolete) HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Resuming the old 1995 plan of previous HTTP Working Group, in 1997 an *HTTP-NG Working Group* was formed to develop a new HTTP protocol named HTTP-NG (HTTP New Generation).
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A few proposals / drafts were produced for the new protocol to use multiplexing of HTTP transactions inside a single TCP/IP connection, but in 1999, the group stopped its activity passing the technical problems to IETF.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2007, the IETF HTTP Working Group (HTTP WG bis or HTTPbis) was restarted firstly to revise and clarify previous HTTP/1.1 specifications and secondly to write and refine future HTTP/2 specifications (named httpbis).
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2009, Google announced SPDY – a binary protocol they developed to speed up web traffic between browsers and servers.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In many tests, using SPDY was indeed faster than using HTTP/1.1.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] SPDY was integrated into Google's Chromium and then into other major web browsers.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some of the ideas about multiplexing HTTP streams over a single TCP connection were taken from various sources, including the work of W3C HTTP-NG Working Group.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2012, HTTP Working Group (HTTPbis) announced the need for a new protocol; initially considering aspects of SPDY and eventually deciding to derive the new protocol from SPDY.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 2015, HTTP/2 was published as RFC 7540.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol was quickly adopted by web browsers already supporting SPDY and more slowly by web servers.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As of 2022, HTTP/0.9 support has not been officially, completely deprecated and is still present in many web servers and browsers (for server responses only), even if usually disabled.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is unclear how long it will take to decommission HTTP/0.9.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2020, the first drafts of HTTP/3 were published and major web browsers and web servers started to adopt it.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] On 6 June 2022, IETF standardized HTTP/3 as RFC 9114.
[src:reqwest-rust/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 2022, RFC documents were published that deprecated many of the previous documents and introducing a few minor changes and a refactoring of HTTP semantics description into a separate document.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] The `reqwest` crate provides a convenient, higher-level HTTP `Client`.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] It handles many of the things that most people just expect an HTTP client to do for them.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] The `reqwest::Client` is asynchronous (requiring Tokio).
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] For applications wishing to only make a few HTTP requests, the `reqwest::blocking` API may be more convenient.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] For private advice, support, reviews, access to the maintainer, and the like, reach out for commercial support.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] For a single request, you can use the `get` shortcut method.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] There are several ways you can set the body of a request.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] The basic one is by using the `body()` method of a `RequestBuilder`.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] This lets you set the exact raw bytes of what the body should be.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] It accepts various types, including `String` and `Vec<u8>`.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] If you wish to pass a custom type, you can use the `reqwest::Body` constructors.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] It’s very common to want to send form data in a request body.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] This can be done with any type that can be serialized into form data.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] This can be an array of tuples, or a `HashMap`, or a custom type that implements `Serialize`.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] There is also a `json` method helper on the `RequestBuilder` that works in a similar fashion the `form` method.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] It can take any value that can be serialized into JSON.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] By default, a `Client` will automatically handle HTTP redirects, having a maximum redirect chain of 10 hops.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] To customize this behavior, a `redirect::Policy` can be used with a `ClientBuilder`.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] The automatic storing and sending of session cookies can be enabled with the `cookie_store` method on `ClientBuilder`.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] System proxies look in environment variables to set HTTP or HTTPS proxies.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] `HTTP_PROXY` or `http_proxy` provide HTTP proxies for HTTP connections while `HTTPS_PROXY` or `https_proxy` provide HTTPS proxies for HTTPS connections.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] `ALL_PROXY` or `all_proxy` provide proxies for both HTTP and HTTPS connections.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] If both the all proxy and HTTP or HTTPS proxy variables are set the more specific HTTP or HTTPS proxies take precedence.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] These can be overwritten by adding a `Proxy` to `ClientBuilder` i.e.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] `let proxy = reqwest::Proxy::http("https://secure.example")?;` or disabled by calling `ClientBuilder::no_proxy()`.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] A `Client` will use transport layer security (TLS) by default to connect to HTTPS destinations.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] The Client implementation automatically switches to the WASM one when the target_arch is wasm32, the usage is basically the same as the async api.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] Some of the features are disabled in wasm : `tls`, `cookie`, `blocking`, as well as various `ClientBuilder` methods such as `timeout()` and `connector_layer()`.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] TLS and cookies are provided through the browser environment, so reqwest can issue TLS requests with cookies, but has limited configuration.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] Some feature flags require additional opt-in by the application, by setting a `reqwest_unstable` flag.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] These features are unstable, and experimental.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] Details about them may be changed in patch releases.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] Support this project by becoming a sponsor.
[src:reqwest-rust/latest-reqwest] A provider for Unix Domain Socket paths.
[src:reqwest-rust/representational-state-transfer] REST has been employed throughout the software industry to create stateless, reliable, web-based applications.
[src:reqwest-rust/representational-state-transfer] The term *representational state transfer* was introduced and defined in 2000 by computer scientist Roy Fielding in his doctoral dissertation.
[src:reqwest-rust/representational-state-transfer] It means that a server will respond with the representation of a resource (today, it will most often be an HTML document) and that resource will contain hypermedia links that can be followed to make the state of the system change.
[src:reqwest-rust/representational-state-transfer] Any such request will in turn receive the representation of a resource, and so on.
[src:reqwest-rust/representational-state-transfer] An important consequence is that the only identifier that needs to be known is the identifier of the first resource requested, and all other identifiers will be discovered.
[src:reqwest-rust/representational-state-transfer] This means that those identifiers can change without the need to inform the client beforehand and that client and server must be inherently loosely coupled.
[src:reqwest-rust/representational-state-transfer] The Web began to enter everyday use in 1993–1994, when websites for general use started to become available.
[src:reqwest-rust/representational-state-transfer] At the time, only a fragmented description existed of the Web's architecture, and there was pressure within the community to agree on a standard for the Web interface protocols.
[src:reqwest-rust/representational-state-transfer] For instance, several experimental extensions had been added to the communication protocol (HTTP) to support proxies, and more extensions were being proposed, but there was a need for a formal Web architecture with which to evaluate the impact of these changes.
[src:reqwest-rust/representational-state-transfer] The W3C and IETF working groups together started work on creating formal descriptions of the Web's three primary standards: URI, HTTP, and HTML.
[src:reqwest-rust/representational-state-transfer] Fielding defined REST in his 2000 PhD dissertation "Architectural Styles and the Design of Network-based Software Architectures" at UC Irvine.
[src:reqwest-rust/representational-state-transfer] To create the REST architectural style, Fielding identified the requirements that apply when creating a world-wide network-based application, such as the need for a low entry barrier to enable global adoption.
[src:reqwest-rust/representational-state-transfer] He also surveyed many existing architectural styles for network-based applications, identifying which features are shared with other styles, such as caching and client–server features, and those which are unique to REST, such as the concept of resources.
[src:reqwest-rust/representational-state-transfer] Fielding was trying to both categorise the existing architecture of the current implementation and identify which aspects should be considered central to the behavioural and performance requirements of the Web.
[src:reqwest-rust/representational-state-transfer] By their nature, architectural styles are independent of any specific implementation, and while REST was created as part of the development of the Web standards, the implementation of the Web does not obey every constraint in the REST architectural style.
[src:reqwest-rust/representational-state-transfer] Mismatches can occur due to ignorance or oversight, but the existence of the REST architectural style means that they can be identified before they become standardised.
[src:reqwest-rust/representational-state-transfer] For example, Fielding identified the embedding of session information in URIs as a violation of the constraints of REST which can negatively affect shared caching and server scalability.
[src:reqwest-rust/representational-state-transfer] HTTP cookies also violate REST constraints because they can become out of sync with the browser's application state, making them unreliable; they also contain opaque data that can be a concern for privacy and security.
[src:reqwest-rust/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style is designed for network-based applications, specifically client-server applications.
[src:reqwest-rust/representational-state-transfer] But more than that, it is designed for Internet-scale usage, so the coupling between the *user agent* (client) and the *origin server* must be as loose as possible to facilitate large-scale adoption.
[src:reqwest-rust/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style defines six guiding constraints.
[src:reqwest-rust/representational-state-transfer] When these constraints are applied to the system architecture, it gains desirable non-functional properties, such as performance, scalability, simplicity, modifiability, visibility, portability, and reliability.
[src:reqwest-rust/representational-state-transfer] The uniform interface constraint is fundamental to the design of any RESTful system.
[src:reqwest-rust/representational-state-transfer] It simplifies and decouples the architecture, which enables each part to evolve independently.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports multiple programming paradigms.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] It was influenced by ideas from functional programming, including immutability, higher-order functions, algebraic data types, and pattern matching.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] It also supports object-oriented programming via structs, enums, traits, and methods.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust enforces memory safety (i.e., that all references point to valid memory) without a conventional garbage collector; instead, memory safety errors and data races are prevented by the "borrow checker", which tracks the object lifetime of references at compile time.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Software developer Graydon Hoare created Rust in 2006 while working at Mozilla, which officially sponsored the project in 2009.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The first stable release, Rust 1.0, was published in May 2015.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The project has been sponsored by the Rust Foundation since February 2021.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust has been adopted by many software projects, especially web services and system software.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] It has been studied academically and has a growing community of developers.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust began as a personal project by Mozilla employee Graydon Hoare in 2006.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] According to *MIT Technology Review*, he started the project due to his frustration with a broken elevator in his apartment building whose software had crashed, and named the language after the group of fungi of the same name that is "over-engineered for survival".
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] During the time period between 2006 and 2009, Rust was not publicized to others at Mozilla and was written in Hoare's free time; Hoare began speaking about the language around 2009 after a small group at Mozilla became interested in the project.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Hoare cited languages from the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s as influences — including CLU, BETA, Mesa, NIL, Erlang, Newsqueak, Napier, Hermes, Sather, Alef, and Limbo.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] During the early years, the Rust compiler was written in about 38,000 lines of OCaml.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Early Rust contained several features no longer present today, including explicit object-oriented programming via an `obj` keyword and a typestates system for variable state changes, such as going from uninitialized to initialized.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Mozilla officially sponsored the Rust project in 2009.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Brendan Eich and other executives, intrigued by the possibility of using Rust for a safe web browser engine, placed engineers on the project including Patrick Walton, Niko Matsakis, Felix Klock, and Manish Goregaokar.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] A conference room taken by the project developers was dubbed "the nerd cave," with a sign placed outside the door.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] During this time period, work had shifted from the initial OCaml compiler to a self-hosting compiler (*i.e.*, written in Rust) targeting LLVM.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The ownership system was in place by 2010.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust logo was developed in 2011 based on a bicycle chainring.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust 0.1 became the first public release on January 20, 2012 for Windows, Linux, and MacOS.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The early 2010s witnessed increasing involvement from full-time engineers at Mozilla and open source volunteers outside Mozilla.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The years from 2012 to 2015 were marked by substantial changes to the Rust type system.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory management through the ownership system was gradually consolidated and expanded.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] By 2013, the garbage collector was rarely used, and was removed in favor of the ownership system.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Other features were removed in order to simplify the language, including typestates, the `pure` keyword, various specialized pointer types, and syntax support for channels.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] According to Steve Klabnik, Rust was influenced during this period by developers coming from C++ (e.g., low-level performance of features), scripting languages (e.g., Cargo and package management), and functional programming (e.g., type systems development).
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Graydon Hoare stepped down from Rust in 2013.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] After Hoare's departure, it evolved organically under a federated governance structure, with a "core team" of initially six people, and around 30-40 developers total across various other teams.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] A Request for Comments (RFC) process for new language features was added in March 2014.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The core team would grow to nine people by 2016 with over 1600 RFCs.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Dobb's Journal* in January 2014, while Rust was "widely viewed as a remarkably elegant language", adoption slowed because it radically changed from version to version.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust development at this time focused on finalizing features for version 1.0 so that it could begin promising backward compatibility.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Six years after Mozilla's sponsorship, Rust 1.0 was published and became the first stable release on May 15, 2015.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] A year later, the Rust compiler had accumulated over 1,400 contributors, and there were over 5,000 third-party libraries published on the Rust package management website Crates.io.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The development of the Servo browser engine continued in parallel with Rust, jointly funded by Mozilla and Samsung.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The teams behind the two projects worked in close collaboration; new features in Rust were tested out by the Servo team, and new features in Servo were used to give feedback back to the Rust team.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The first version of Servo was released in 2016.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The Firefox web browser shipped with Rust code as of 2016 (version 45), but components of Servo did not appear in Firefox until September 2017 (version 57) as part of the Gecko and Quantum projects.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Improvements were made to the Rust toolchain ecosystem during the years following 1.0 including Rustfmt, integrated development environment integration, and a regular compiler testing and release cycle.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's community gained a code of conduct and an IRC chat for discussion.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The earliest known adoption outside of Mozilla was by individual projects at Samsung, Facebook (now Meta Platforms), Dropbox, and Tilde, Inc., the company behind ember.js.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Engineers cited performance, lack of a garbage collector, safety, and pleasantness of working in the language as reasons for the adoption.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Amazon developers cited a finding by Portuguese researchers that Rust code used less energy compared to similar code written in Java.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] In August 2020, Mozilla laid off 250 of its 1,000 employees worldwide, as part of a corporate restructuring caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The event raised concerns about the future of Rust.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] In the following week, the Rust Core Team acknowledged the severe impact of the layoffs and announced that plans for a Rust foundation were underway.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The first goal of the foundation would be to take ownership of all trademarks and domain names and to take financial responsibility for their costs.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] On February 8, 2021, the formation of the Rust Foundation was announced by five founding companies: Amazon Web Services, Google, Huawei, Microsoft, and Mozilla.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The foundation would provide financial support for Rust developers in the form of grants and server funding.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] In a blog post published on April 6, 2021, Google announced support for Rust within the Android Open Source Project as an alternative to C/C++.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] On November 22, 2021, the Moderation Team, which was responsible for enforcing the community code of conduct, announced their resignation "in protest of the Core Team placing themselves unaccountable to anyone but themselves".
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] In May 2022, members of the Rust leadership council posted a public response to the incident.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust Foundation posted a draft for a new trademark policy on April 6, 2023, which resulted in widespread negative reactions from Rust users and contributors.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The trademark policy included rules for how the Rust logo and name could be used.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's syntax is similar to that of C and C++, although many of its features were influenced by functional programming languages such as OCaml.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Hoare has described Rust as targeted at frustrated C++ developers.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Below is a "Hello, World!" program in Rust.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The `fn` keyword denotes a function, and the `println!` macro (see § Macros) prints the message to standard output.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Statements in Rust are separated by semicolons.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Variables in Rust are defined through the `let` keyword.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The example below assigns a value to the variable with name `foo` of type `i32` and outputs its value; the type annotation `: i32` can be omitted.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Variables are immutable by default, unless the `mut` keyword is added.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The following example uses `//`, which denotes the start of a comment.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Multiple `let` expressions can define multiple variables with the same name, known as variable shadowing.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing allows transforming variables without having to name the variables differently.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing is also possible for values of different types.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] A *block expression* is delimited by curly brackets.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] An `if` conditional expression executes code based on whether the given value is `true`.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] `else` can be used for when the value evaluates to `false`, and `else if` can be used for combining multiple expressions.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] `while` can be used to repeat a block of code while a condition is met.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] For loops in Rust loop over elements of a collection.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] `for` expressions work over any iterator type.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] In the above code, `4..=10` is a value of type `Range` which implements the `Iterator` trait.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The code within the curly braces is applied to each element returned by the iterator.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Iterators can be combined with functions over iterators like `map`, `filter`, and `sum`.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] More generally, the `loop` keyword allows repeating a portion of code until a `break` occurs.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] `break` may optionally exit the loop with a value.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] In the case of nested loops, labels denoted by `'label_name` can be used to break an outer loop rather than the innermost loop.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The `match` and `if let` expressions can be used for pattern matching.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust is strongly typed and statically typed, meaning that the types of all variables must be known at compilation time.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Assigning a value of a particular type to a differently typed variable causes a compilation error.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Type inference is used to determine the type of variables if unspecified.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The type `()`, called the "unit type" in Rust, is a concrete type that has exactly one value.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] It occupies no memory (as it represents the absence of value).
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] All functions that do not have an indicated return type implicitly return `()`.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] It is similar to `void` in other C-style languages; however, `void` denotes the absence of a type and cannot have any value.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The default integer type is `i32`, and the default floating point type is `f64`.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] If the type of a literal number is not explicitly provided, it is either inferred from the context or the default type is used.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Integer types in Rust are named based on the signedness and the number of bits the type takes.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, `i32` is a signed integer that takes 32 bits of storage, whereas `u8` is unsigned and only takes 8 bits of storage.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] `isize` and `usize` take storage depending on the memory address bus width of the compilation target.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, when building for 32-bit targets, both types will take up 32 bits of space.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals are in base-10, but different radices are supported with prefixes, for example, `0b11` for binary numbers, `0o567` for octals, and `0xDB` for hexadecimals.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals default to `i32` as its type.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Suffixes such as `4u32` can be used to explicitly set the type of a literal.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Byte literals such as `b'X'` are available to represent the ASCII value (as a `u8`) of a specific character.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The Boolean type is referred to as `bool` which can take a value of either `true` or `false`.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] A `char` takes up 32 bits of space and represents a Unicode scalar value: a Unicode codepoint that is not a surrogate.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] IEEE 754 floating point numbers are supported with `f32` for single precision floats and `f64` for double precision floats.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Compound types can contain multiple values.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Tuples are fixed-size lists that can contain values whose types can be different.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Arrays are fixed-size lists whose values are of the same type.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's ownership system consists of rules that ensure memory safety without using a garbage collector.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] At compile time, each value must be attached to a variable called the *owner* of that value, and every value must have exactly one owner.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Values are moved between different owners through assignment or passing a value as a function parameter.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Values can also be *borrowed,* meaning they are temporarily passed to a different function before being returned to the owner.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Because of these ownership rules, Rust types are known as *affine types*, meaning each value may be used at most once.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] This enforces a form of software fault isolation as the owner of a value is solely responsible for its correctness and deallocation.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] When a value goes out of scope, it is *dropped* by running its destructor.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The destructor may be programmatically defined through implementing the `Drop` trait.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] This helps manage resources such as file handles, network sockets, and locks, since when objects are dropped, the resources associated with them are closed or released automatically.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Object lifetime refers to the period of time during which a reference is valid; that is, the time between the object creation and destruction.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] These *lifetimes* are implicitly associated with all Rust reference types.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] While often inferred, they can also be indicated explicitly with named lifetime parameters (often denoted `'a`, `'b`, and so on).
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] A value's lifetime in Rust is inferred from the set of locations in the source code (i.e., function, line, and column numbers) for which a variable is valid.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, a reference to a local variable has a lifetime from the expression it is declared in up until the last use of it.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The borrow checker in the Rust compiler then enforces that references are only used in the locations of the source code where the associated lifetime is valid.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] In the example above, storing a reference to variable `x` in `r` is valid, as variable `x` has a longer lifetime (`'a`) than variable `r` (`'b`).
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Since the lifetime of the referenced variable (`'b`) is shorter than the lifetime of the variable holding the reference (`'a`), the borrow checker errors, preventing `x` from being used from outside its scope.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Lifetimes can be indicated using explicit *lifetime parameters* on function arguments.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] In the compiler, ownership and lifetimes work together to prevent memory safety issues such as dangling pointers.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] User-defined types are created with the `struct` or `enum` keywords.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The `struct` keyword is used to denote a record type that groups multiple related values.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] `enum`s can take on different variants at runtime, with their capabilities similar to algebraic data types found in functional programming languages.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Both records and enum variants can contain fields with different types.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Alternative names, or aliases, for the same type can be defined with the `type` keyword.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The `impl` keyword can define methods for a user-defined type.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Data and functions are defined separately.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Implementations fulfill a role similar to that of classes within other languages.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust standard library defines and implements many widely used custom data types, including core data structures such as `Vec`, `Option`, and `HashMap`, as well as smart pointer types.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides a way to exclude most of the standard library using the attribute `#![no_std]`, for applications such as embedded devices.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Internally, the standard library is divided into three parts, `core`, `alloc`, and `std`, where `std` and `alloc` are excluded by `#![no_std]`.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Similarly, Rust's result type `Result<T, E>` holds either a successfully computed value (the `Ok` variant) or an error (the `Err` variant).
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Like `Option`, the use of `Result` means that the inner value cannot be used directly; programmers must use a `match` expression, syntactic sugar such as `?` (the "try" operator), or an explicit `unwrap` assertion to access it.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Both `Option` and `Result` are used throughout the standard library and are a fundamental part of Rust's explicit approach to handling errors and missing data.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The `&` and `&mut` reference types are guaranteed to not be null and point to valid memory.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The raw pointer types `*const` and `*mut` opt out of the safety guarantees, thus they may be null or invalid; however, it is impossible to dereference them unless the code is explicitly declared unsafe through the use of an `unsafe` block.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Unlike dereferencing, the creation of raw pointers is allowed inside safe Rust code.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides no implicit type conversion (coercion) between most primitive types.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] But, explicit type conversion (casting) can be performed using the `as` keyword.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports polymorphism through traits, generic functions, and trait objects.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The example above includes a method `is_zero` which provides a default implementation that may be overridden when implementing the trait.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] In the examples above, `Num: Zero` as well as `where Self: PartialEq` are trait bounds that constrain the type to only allow types that implement `Zero` or `PartialEq`.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Within a trait or impl, `Self` refers to the type that the code is implementing.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Generics can be used in functions to allow implementing a behavior for different types without repeating the same code (see bounded parametric polymorphism).
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Generic functions can be written in relation to other generics, without knowing the actual type.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, traits use static dispatch: the compiler monomorphizes the function for each concrete type instance, yielding performance equivalent to type-specific code at the cost of longer compile times and larger binaries.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] When the exact type is not known at compile time, Rust provides trait objects `&dyn Trait` and `Box<dyn Trait>`.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Trait object calls use dynamic dispatch via a lookup table; a trait object is a "fat pointer" carrying both a data pointer and a method table pointer.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] This indirection adds a small runtime cost, but it keeps a single copy of the code and reduces binary size.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Only "object-safe" traits are eligible to be used as trait objects.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] This approach is similar to duck typing, where all data types that implement a given trait can be treated as functionally interchangeable.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] If an element in the list does not implement the `Display` trait, it will cause a compile-time error.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory and other resources are instead managed through the "resource acquisition is initialization" convention, with optional reference counting.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides deterministic management of resources, with very low overhead.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Values are allocated on the stack by default, and all dynamic allocations must be explicit.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The built-in reference types using the `&` symbol do not involve run-time reference counting.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The safety and validity of the underlying pointers are verified at compile time, preventing dangling pointers and other forms of undefined behavior.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's type system separates shared, immutable references of the form `&T` from unique, mutable references of the form `&mut T`.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] A mutable reference can be coerced to an immutable reference, but not vice versa.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's memory safety checks (See #Safety) may be circumvented through the use of `unsafe` blocks.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] This allows programmers to dereference arbitrary raw pointers, call external code, or perform other low-level functionality not allowed by safe Rust.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Some low-level functionality enabled in this way includes volatile memory access, architecture-specific intrinsics, type punning, and inline assembly.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Unsafe code is needed, for example, in the implementation of data structures.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] A frequently cited example is that it is difficult or impossible to implement doubly linked lists in safe Rust.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Programmers using unsafe Rust are considered responsible for upholding Rust's memory and type safety requirements, for example, that no two mutable references exist pointing to the same location.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] If programmers write code that violates these requirements, this results in undefined behavior.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust documentation includes a list of behaviors considered undefined, including accessing dangling or misaligned pointers, or breaking the aliasing rules for references.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Macros allow the generation and transformation of Rust code to reduce repetition.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Macros come in two forms, with *declarative macros* defined through `macro_rules!`, and *procedural macros*, which are defined in separate crates.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] A declarative macro (also called a "macro by example") is a macro, defined using the `macro_rules!` keyword, that uses pattern matching to determine its expansion.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] In this example, the macro named `sum` is defined using the form `macro_rules! sum {` `(...) => { ... } }`.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The first part inside the parentheses of the definition, the macro pattern `( $initial:expr $(, $expr:expr )* $(,)? )` specifies the structure of input it can take.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Here, `$initial:expr` represents the first expression, while `$(, $expr:expr )*` means there can be zero or more additional comma-separated expressions after it.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The trailing `$(,)?` allows the caller to optionally include a final comma without causing an error.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The second part, after the arrow `=>`, describes what code will be generated when the macro is invoked.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] In this case, `$initial $(+ $expr)*` means that the generated code will start with the first expression, followed by a `+` and each of the additional expressions in sequence.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The `*` again means "repeat this pattern zero or more times".
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] This means, when the macro is later called in line 8, as `sum!(1, 2, 3)`, the macro will resolve to `1 + 2 + 3` representing the addition of all of the passed expressions.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Procedural macros are Rust functions that run and modify the compiler's input token stream, before any other components are compiled.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] They are generally more flexible than declarative macros, but are more difficult to maintain due to their complexity.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports the creation of foreign function interfaces (FFI) through the `extern` keyword.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] A function that uses the C calling convention can be written using `extern "C" fn`.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The `#[repr(C)]` attribute enables deterministic memory layouts for `struct`s and `enum`s for use across FFI boundaries.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] External libraries such as `bindgen` and `cxx` can generate Rust bindings for C/C++.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Safety properties guaranteed by Rust include memory safety, type safety, and data race freedom.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] As described above, these guarantees can be circumvented by using the `unsafe` keyword.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory safety includes the absence of dereferences to null, dangling, and misaligned pointers, and the absence of buffer overflows and double free errors.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory leaks may occur as a result of creating reference-counted pointers that point at each other (a reference cycle) or can be deliberately created through calling `Box::leak`.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust ecosystem includes its compiler, its standard library, and additional components for software development.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Component installation is typically managed by `rustup`, a Rust toolchain installer developed by the Rust project.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust compiler, `rustc`, compiles Rust code into binaries.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] First, the compiler parses the source code into an AST.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The compiler backend is then invoked as a subcomponent to apply optimizations and translate the resulting IR into object code.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Finally, a linker is used to combine the object(s) into a single executable image.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] rustc uses LLVM as its compiler backend by default, but it also supports using alternative backends such as GCC and Cranelift.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The intention of those alternative backends is to increase platform coverage of Rust or to improve compilation times.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo is Rust's build system and package manager.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] It downloads, compiles, distributes, and uploads packages—called *crates*—that are maintained in an official registry.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] It also acts as a front-end for Clippy and other Rust components.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, Cargo sources its dependencies from the user-contributed registry *crates.io*, but Git repositories, crates in the local filesystem, and other external sources can also be specified as dependencies.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo supports reproducible builds through two metadata files: Cargo.toml and Cargo.lock.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo.toml declares each package used and their version requirements.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo.lock is generated automatically during dependency resolution and records exact versions of all dependencies, including transitive dependencies.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] It formats whitespace and indentation to produce code in accordance with a common style, unless otherwise specified.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] It can be invoked as a standalone program or from a Rust project through Cargo.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Clippy is Rust's built-in linting tool to improve the correctness, performance, and readability of Rust code.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Following Rust 1.0, new features are developed in *nightly* versions, which are released daily.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] During each six-week release cycle, changes to nightly versions are released to beta, while changes from the previous beta version are released to a new stable version.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Every two or three years, a new "edition" is produced.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Editions are released to allow making limited breaking changes, such as promoting `await` to a keyword to support async/await features.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Crates targeting different editions can interoperate with each other, so a crate can upgrade to a new edition even if its callers or its dependencies still target older editions.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Migration to a new edition can be assisted with automated tooling.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Since it performs no garbage collection, Rust is often faster than other memory-safe languages.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Most of Rust's memory safety guarantees impose no runtime overhead, with the notable exception of array indexing which is checked at runtime by default.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The performance impact of array indexing bounds checks varies, but can be significant in some cases.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Many of Rust's features are so-called *zero-cost abstractions*, meaning they are optimized away at compile time and incur no runtime penalty.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The ownership and borrowing system permits zero-copy implementations for some performance-sensitive tasks, such as parsing.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Static dispatch is used by default to eliminate method calls, except for methods called on dynamic trait objects.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The compiler uses inline expansion to eliminate function calls and statically dispatched method invocations.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Unlike C and C++, Rust allows the compiler to reorder struct and enum elements unless a `#[repr(C)]` representation attribute is applied.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] This allows the compiler to produce more efficient code in some cases.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Performance improvements in LLVM carry over to Rust.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] In web services, OpenDNS, a DNS resolution service owned by Cisco, uses Rust internally.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Amazon Web Services uses Rust in "performance-sensitive components" of services.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2019, AWS open-sourced Firecracker, a virtualization solution primarily written in Rust.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft Azure IoT Edge, a platform used to run Azure services on IoT devices, has components implemented in Rust.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft also uses Rust to run containerized modules with WebAssembly and Kubernetes.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Cloudflare, a company providing content delivery network services, used Rust to build a new web proxy named Pingora for increased performance and efficiency.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The npm package manager used Rust for its production authentication service in 2019.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] In operating systems, the Linux kernel began introducing experimental support for Rust code in Version 6.1 in late 2022, as part of the Rust for Linux project.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The first drivers written in Rust were included in version 6.8.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2025, kernel developers at the Linux Kernel Developers Summit determined the project to be a success, and Rust usage for kernel code will no longer be considered experimental.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The Android developers used Rust in 2021 to rewrite existing components.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft has rewritten parts of Windows in Rust.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The r9 project aims to re-implement Plan 9 from Bell Labs in Rust.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust has also been used in the development of new operating systems such as Redox, a "Unix-like" operating system and microkernel, Theseus, an experimental operating system with modular state management, and most of Fuchsia.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust is used for command-line tools and operating system components such as stratisd, a file system manager and COSMIC, a desktop environment by System76.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] In web development, Deno, a secure runtime for JavaScript and TypeScript, is built on top of V8 using Rust and Tokio.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Other notable adoptions in this space include Ruffle, an open-source SWF emulator, and Polkadot, an open source blockchain and cryptocurrency platform.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Components from the Servo browser engine (funded by Mozilla and Samsung) were incorporated in the Gecko browser engine underlying Firefox.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] In January 2023, Google (Alphabet) announced support for using third party Rust libraries in Chromium.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] In other uses, Discord, an instant messaging software company, rewrote parts of its system in Rust for increased performance in 2020.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] In the same year, Dropbox announced that its file synchronization had been rewritten in Rust.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Facebook (Meta) used Rust to redesign its system that manages source code for internal projects.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] In the 2025 Stack Overflow Developer Survey, 14.8% of respondents had recently done extensive development in Rust.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The survey named Rust the "most admired programming language" annually from 2016 to 2025 (inclusive), as measured by the number of existing developers interested in continuing to work in the language.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2025, 29.2% of developers not currently working in Rust expressed an interest in doing so.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's safety and performance have been investigated in programming languages research.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] In other fields, a journal article published to *Proceedings of the International Astronomical Union* used Rust to simulate multi-planet systems.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] An article published in *Nature* shared stories of bioinformaticians using Rust.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Both articles cited Rust's performance and safety as advantages, and the learning curve as being a primary drawback to Rust adoption.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The 2025 DARPA project TRACTOR aims to automatically translate C to Rust using techniques such as static analysis, dynamic analysis, and large language models.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] According to the *MIT Technology Review*, the Rust community has been seen as "unusually friendly" to newcomers and particularly attracted people from the queer community, partly due to its code of conduct.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] Inclusiveness has been cited as an important factor for some Rust developers.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The official Rust blog collects and publishes demographic data each year.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The **Rust Foundation** is a non-profit membership organization incorporated in United States; it manages the Rust trademark, infrastructure, and assets.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] It was established on February 8, 2021, with five founding corporate members (Amazon Web Services, Huawei, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla).
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The foundation's board was chaired by Shane Miller, with Ashley Williams as interim executive director.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] In late 2021, Rebecca Rumbul became executive director and CEO.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust project is maintained by 8 top-level *teams* as of November 2025: the leadership council, compiler team, dev tools team, infrastructure team, language team, launching pad, library team, and moderation team.
[src:reqwest-rust/rust-programming-language] The leadership council oversees the project and is formed by representatives among the other teams.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS protocol aims primarily to provide security, including privacy (confidentiality), integrity, and authenticity through the use of cryptography, such as the use of certificates, between two or more communicating computer applications.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] It runs in the presentation layer and is itself composed of two layers: the TLS record and the TLS handshake protocols.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] The closely-related Datagram Transport Layer Security (DTLS) is a communications protocol that provides security to datagram-based applications.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] In technical writing, references to "(D)TLS" are often seen when it applies to both versions.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS is a proposed Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) standard, first defined in 1999, and the current version is TLS 1.3, defined in August 2018.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS builds on the now-deprecated **SSL** (**Secure Sockets Layer**) specifications (1994, 1995, 1996) developed by Netscape Communications for adding the HTTPS protocol to their Netscape Navigator web browser.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Client–server applications use the TLS protocol to communicate across a network in a way designed to prevent eavesdropping and tampering.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Since applications can communicate either with or without TLS (or SSL), it is necessary for the client to request that the server set up a TLS connection.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] One of the main ways of achieving this is to use a different port number for TLS connections.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Port 80 is typically used for unencrypted HTTP traffic while port 443 is the common port used for encrypted HTTPS traffic.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Another mechanism is to make a protocol-specific STARTTLS request to the server to switch the connection to TLS – for example, when using some mail and news protocols.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Once the client and server have agreed to use TLS, they negotiate a stateful connection by using a handshaking procedure (see § TLS handshake).
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] The protocols use a handshake with an asymmetric cipher to establish not only cipher settings but also a session-specific shared key with which further communication is encrypted using a symmetric cipher.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] This concludes the handshake and begins the secured connection, which is encrypted and decrypted with the session key until the connection closes.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] If any one of the above steps fails, then the TLS handshake fails and the connection is not created.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Note that TLS 1.3 only allows key exchange algorithms providing forward secrecy.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Consequently, establishing a PreMasterSecret using the server's public and private key is only available in TLS 1.2 and below.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS and SSL do not fit neatly into any single layer of the OSI model or the TCP/IP model.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS runs "on top of some reliable transport protocol (e.g., TCP)", which would imply that it is above the transport layer.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] It serves encryption to higher layers, which is normally the function of the presentation layer.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] However, applications generally use TLS as if it were a transport layer, even though applications using TLS must actively control initiating TLS handshakes and handling of exchanged authentication certificates.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS supports many different methods for exchanging keys, encrypting data, and authenticating message integrity.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] As a result, secure configuration of TLS involves many configurable parameters, and not all choices provide all of the privacy-related properties described in the list above (see the tables below § Key exchange, § Cipher security, and § Data integrity).
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Attempts have been made to subvert aspects of the communications security that TLS seeks to provide, and the protocol has been revised several times to address these security threats.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Developers of web browsers have repeatedly revised their products to defend against potential security weaknesses after these were discovered (see TLS/SSL support history of web browsers).
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Datagram Transport Layer Security, abbreviated DTLS, is a related communications protocol providing security to datagram-based applications by allowing them to communicate in a way designed to prevent eavesdropping, tampering, or message forgery.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] The DTLS protocol is based on the stream-oriented Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol and is intended to provide similar security guarantees.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] As the DTLS protocol datagram preserves the semantics of the underlying transport, the application does not suffer from the delays associated with stream protocols.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] However, the application has to deal with packet reordering, loss of datagram and data larger than the size of a datagram network packet.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Because DTLS uses UDP or SCTP rather than TCP, it avoids the TCP meltdown problem, when being used to create a VPN tunnel.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] The original 2006 release of DTLS version 1.0 was not a standalone document.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] It was given as a series of deltas to TLS 1.1.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Similarly the follow-up 2012 release of DTLS is a delta to TLS 1.2.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] It was given the version number of DTLS 1.2 to match its TLS version.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Lastly, the 2022 DTLS 1.3 is a delta to TLS 1.3.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Like the two previous versions, DTLS 1.3 is intended to provide "equivalent security guarantees [to TLS 1.3] with the exception of order protection/non-replayability".
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Many VPN clients including Cisco AnyConnect & InterCloud Fabric, OpenConnect, ZScaler tunnel, F5 Networks Edge VPN Client, and Citrix Systems NetScaler use DTLS to secure UDP traffic.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] In addition all modern web browsers support DTLS-SRTP for WebRTC.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] It was intended to complement the rapidly emerging new OSI internet standards moving forward both in the U.S. government's GOSIP Profiles and in the huge ITU-ISO JTC1 internet effort internationally.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] As part of the project, researchers designed a protocol called SP4 (*security protocol* in layer 4 of the OSI system).
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] This was later renamed the Transport Layer Security Protocol (TLSP) and subsequently published in 1995 as international standard ITU-T X.274|ISO/IEC 10736:1995.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Despite the name similarity, this is distinct from today's TLS.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] SNP was published and presented in the 1994 USENIX Summer Technical Conference.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] The SNP project was funded by a grant from NSA to Professor Simon Lam at UT-Austin in 1991.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Secure Network Programming won the 2004 ACM Software System Award.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Netscape developed the original SSL protocols, and Taher Elgamal, chief scientist at Netscape Communications from 1995 to 1998, has been described as the "father of SSL".
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL version 1.0 was never publicly released because of serious security flaws in the protocol.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Version 2.0, after being released in February 1995 was quickly found to contain a number of security and usability flaws.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] It used the same cryptographic keys for message authentication and encryption.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] It had a weak MAC construction that used the MD5 hash function with a secret prefix, making it vulnerable to length extension attacks.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] It also provided no protection for either the opening handshake or an explicit message close, both of which meant man-in-the-middle attacks could go undetected.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Moreover, SSL 2.0 assumed a single service and a fixed domain certificate, conflicting with the widely used feature of virtual hosting in Web servers, so most websites were effectively impaired from using SSL.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] These flaws necessitated the complete redesign of the protocol to SSL version 3.0.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Released in 1996, it was produced by Paul Kocher working with Netscape engineers Phil Karlton and Alan Freier, with a reference implementation by Christopher Allen and Tim Dierks of Certicom.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Newer versions of SSL/TLS are based on SSL 3.0.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] The 1996 draft of SSL 3.0 was published by IETF as a historical document in RFC 6101.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL 2.0 was deprecated in 2011 by RFC 6176.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] In 2014, SSL 3.0 was found to be vulnerable to the POODLE attack that affects all block ciphers in SSL; RC4, the only non-block cipher supported by SSL 3.0, is also feasibly broken as used in SSL 3.0.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL 3.0 was deprecated in June 2015 by RFC 7568.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 was first defined in RFC 2246 in January 1999 as an upgrade of SSL Version 3.0, and written by Christopher Allen and Tim Dierks of Certicom.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] As stated in the RFC, "the differences between this protocol and SSL 3.0 are not dramatic, but they are significant enough to preclude interoperability between TLS 1.0 and SSL 3.0".
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Tim Dierks later wrote that these changes, and the renaming from "SSL" to "TLS", were a face-saving gesture to Microsoft, "so it wouldn't look [like] the IETF was just rubberstamping Netscape's protocol".
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] The PCI Council suggested that organizations migrate from TLS 1.0 to TLS 1.1 or higher before June 30, 2018.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] In October 2018, Apple, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla jointly announced they would deprecate TLS 1.0 and 1.1 in March 2020.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 and 1.1 were formally deprecated in RFC 8996 in March 2021.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.1 was defined in RFC 4346 in April 2006.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Support for TLS versions 1.0 and 1.1 was widely deprecated by web sites around 2020, disabling access to Firefox versions before 24 and Chromium-based browsers before 29, though third-party fixes can be applied to Netscape Navigator and older versions of Firefox to add TLS 1.2 support.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.2 was defined in RFC 5246 in August 2008.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] It is based on the earlier TLS 1.1 specification.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] All TLS versions were further refined in RFC 6176 in March 2011, removing their backward compatibility with SSL such that TLS sessions never negotiate the use of Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) version 2.0.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] As of April 2025 there is no formal date for TLS 1.2 to be deprecated.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 was defined in RFC 8446 in August 2018.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] It is based on the earlier TLS 1.2 specification.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Network Security Services (NSS), the cryptography library developed by Mozilla and used by its web browser Firefox, enabled TLS 1.3 by default in February 2017.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 support was subsequently added — but due to compatibility issues for a small number of users, not automatically enabled — to Firefox 52.0, which was released in March 2017.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 was enabled by default in May 2018 with the release of Firefox 60.0.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Google Chrome set TLS 1.3 as the default version for a short time in 2017.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] It then removed it as the default, due to incompatible middleboxes such as Blue Coat web proxies.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] The intolerance of the new version of TLS was protocol ossification; middleboxes had ossified the protocol's version parameter.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] As a result, version 1.3 mimics the wire image of version 1.2.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] This change occurred very late in the design process, only having been discovered during browser deployment.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] The discovery of this intolerance also led to the prior version negotiation strategy, where the highest matching version was picked, being abandoned due to unworkable levels of ossification.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] 'Greasing' an extension point, where one protocol participant claims support for non-existent extensions to ensure that unrecognised-but-actually-existent extensions are tolerated and so to resist ossification, was originally designed for TLS, but it has since been adopted elsewhere.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] During the IETF 100 Hackathon, which took place in Singapore in 2017, the TLS Group worked on adapting open-source applications to use TLS 1.3.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS group was made up of individuals from Japan, United Kingdom, and Mauritius via the cyberstorm.mu team.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] This work was continued in the IETF 101 Hackathon in London, and the IETF 102 Hackathon in Montreal.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] wolfSSL enabled the use of TLS 1.3 as of version 3.11.1, released in May 2017.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] As the first commercial TLS 1.3 implementation, wolfSSL 3.11.1 supported Draft 18 and now supports Draft 28, the final version, as well as many older versions.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] A series of blogs were published on the performance difference between TLS 1.2 and 1.3.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] In September 2018, the popular OpenSSL project released version 1.1.1 of its library, in which support for TLS 1.3 was "the headline new feature".
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Support for TLS 1.3 was added to Secure Channel (schannel) for the GA releases of Windows 11 and Windows Server 2022.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] The Electronic Frontier Foundation praised TLS 1.3 and expressed concern about the variant protocol Enterprise Transport Security (ETS) that intentionally disables important security measures in TLS 1.3.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Originally called Enterprise TLS (eTLS), ETS is a published standard known as the 'ETSI TS103523-3', "Middlebox Security Protocol, Part3: Enterprise Transport Security".
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] It is intended for use entirely within proprietary networks such as banking systems.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] ETS does not support forward secrecy so as to allow third-party organizations connected to the proprietary networks to be able to use their private key to monitor network traffic for the detection of malware and to make it easier to conduct audits.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Despite the claimed benefits, the EFF warned that the loss of forward secrecy could make it easier for data to be exposed along with saying that there are better ways to analyze traffic.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] A digital certificate certifies the ownership of a public key by the named subject of the certificate, and indicates certain expected usages of that key.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] This allows others (relying parties) to rely upon signatures or on assertions made by the private key that corresponds to the certified public key.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Keystores and trust stores can be in various formats, such as .pem, .crt, .pfx, and .jks.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS typically relies on a set of trusted third-party certificate authorities to establish the authenticity of certificates.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Trust is usually anchored in a list of certificates distributed with user agent software, and can be modified by the relying party.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] According to Netcraft, who monitors active TLS certificates, the market-leading certificate authority (CA) has been Symantec since the beginning of their survey (or VeriSign before the authentication services business unit was purchased by Symantec).
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] As of 2015, Symantec accounted for just under a third of all certificates and 44% of the valid certificates used by the 1 million busiest websites, as counted by Netcraft.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] In 2017, Symantec sold its TLS/SSL business to DigiCert.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] In an updated report, it was shown that IdenTrust, DigiCert, and Sectigo are the top 3 certificate authorities in terms of market share since May 2019.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] As a consequence of choosing X.509 certificates, certificate authorities and a public key infrastructure are necessary to verify the relation between a certificate and its owner, as well as to generate, sign, and administer the validity of certificates.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] On April 11, 2025, the CA/Browser Forum approved a ballot that will require all public TLS certificate lifespans to gradually reduce to 47 days by 2029.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Before a client and server can begin to exchange information protected by TLS, they must securely exchange or agree upon an encryption key and a cipher to use when encrypting data (see § Cipher).
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS_DH_anon and TLS_ECDH_anon key agreement methods do not authenticate the server or the user and hence are rarely used because those are vulnerable to man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Only TLS_DHE and TLS_ECDHE provide forward secrecy.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Public key certificates used during exchange/agreement also vary in the size of the public/private encryption keys used during the exchange and hence the robustness of the security provided.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] In July 2013, Google announced that it would no longer use 1024-bit public keys and would switch instead to 2048-bit keys to increase the security of the TLS encryption it provides to its users because the encryption strength is directly related to the key size.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] If libraries implement fixes listed in RFC 5746, this violates the SSL 3.0 specification, which the IETF cannot change unlike TLS.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Most current libraries implement the fix and disregard the violation that this causes.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] The BEAST attack breaks all block ciphers (CBC ciphers) used in SSL 3.0 and TLS 1.0 unless mitigated by the client or the server.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] The POODLE attack breaks all block ciphers (CBC ciphers) used in SSL 3.0 unless mitigated by the client or the server.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] AEAD ciphers (such as GCM and CCM) can only be used in TLS 1.2 or later.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] CBC ciphers can be attacked with the Lucky Thirteen attack if the library is not written carefully to eliminate timing side channels.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] The Sweet32 attack breaks block ciphers with a block size of 64 bits.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Although the key length of 3DES is 168 bits, effective security strength of 3DES is only 112 bits, which is below the recommended minimum of 128 bits.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] IDEA and DES have been removed from TLS 1.2.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] 40-bit strength cipher suites were intentionally designed with reduced key lengths to comply with since-rescinded US regulations forbidding the export of cryptographic software containing certain strong encryption algorithms (see Export of cryptography from the United States).
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] These weak suites are forbidden in TLS 1.1 and later.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Use of RC4 in all versions of TLS is prohibited because RC4 attacks weaken or break RC4 used in SSL/TLS.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] A message authentication code (MAC) is used for data integrity.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] HMAC is used for CBC mode of block ciphers.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Authenticated encryption (AEAD) such as GCM and CCM mode uses AEAD-integrated MAC and does not use HMAC.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] HMAC-based PRF, or HKDF is used for TLS handshake.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] In applications design, TLS is usually implemented on top of Transport Layer protocols, encrypting all of the protocol-related data of protocols such as HTTP, FTP, SMTP, NNTP and XMPP.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Historically, TLS has been used primarily with reliable transport protocols such as the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] However, it has also been implemented with datagram-oriented transport protocols, such as the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) and the Datagram Congestion Control Protocol (DCCP), usage of which has been standardized independently using the term *Datagram Transport Layer Security* (*DTLS*).
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] A primary use of TLS is to secure World Wide Web traffic between a website and a web browser encoded with the HTTP protocol.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] This use of TLS to secure HTTP traffic constitutes the HTTPS protocol.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] As of March 2025, the latest versions of all major web browsers support TLS 1.2 and 1.3 and have them enabled by default, with the exception of IE 11.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 and 1.1 are disabled by default on the latest versions of all major browsers.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Most SSL and TLS programming libraries are free and open-source software.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] A paper presented at the 2012 ACM conference on computer and communications security showed that many applications used some of these SSL libraries incorrectly, leading to vulnerabilities.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] The Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) can also be protected by TLS.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] These applications use public key certificates to verify the identity of endpoints.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS can also be used for tunneling an entire network stack to create a VPN, which is the case with OpenVPN and OpenConnect.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Many vendors have by now married TLS's encryption and authentication capabilities with authorization.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] There has also been substantial development since the late 1990s in creating client technology outside of Web-browsers, in order to enable support for client/server applications.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] Compared to traditional IPsec VPN technologies, TLS has some inherent advantages in firewall and NAT traversal that make it easier to administer for large remote-access populations.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS is also a standard method for protecting Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) application signaling.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS can be used for providing authentication and encryption of the SIP signaling associated with VoIP and other SIP-based applications.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Significant attacks against TLS/SSL are listed below.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, IETF issued an informational RFC summarizing the various known attacks against TLS/SSL.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] A vulnerability of the renegotiation procedure was discovered in August 2009 that can lead to plaintext injection attacks against SSL 3.0 and all current versions of TLS.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] For example, it allows an attacker who can hijack an https connection to splice their own requests into the beginning of the conversation the client has with the web server.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The attacker cannot actually decrypt the client–server communication, so it is different from a typical man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] A short-term fix is for web servers to stop allowing renegotiation, which typically will not require other changes unless client certificate authentication is used.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] To fix the vulnerability, a renegotiation indication extension was proposed for TLS.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] It will require the client and server to include and verify information about previous handshakes in any renegotiation handshakes.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] This extension has been implemented by several libraries.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] A protocol downgrade attack (also called a version rollback attack) tricks a web server into negotiating connections with previous versions of TLS (such as SSLv2) that have long since been abandoned as insecure.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Previous modifications to the original protocols, like **False Start** (adopted and enabled by Google Chrome) or **Snap Start**, reportedly introduced limited TLS protocol downgrade attacks or allowed modifications to the cipher suite list sent by the client to the server.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] In doing so, an attacker might succeed in influencing the cipher suite selection in an attempt to downgrade the cipher suite negotiated to use either a weaker symmetric encryption algorithm or a weaker key exchange.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] A paper presented at an ACM conference on computer and communications security in 2012 demonstrated that the False Start extension was at risk: in certain circumstances it could allow an attacker to recover the encryption keys offline and to access the encrypted data.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Encryption downgrade attacks can force servers and clients to negotiate a connection using cryptographically weak keys.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2014, a man-in-the-middle attack called FREAK was discovered affecting the OpenSSL stack, the default Android web browser, and some Safari browsers.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The attack involved tricking servers into negotiating a TLS connection using cryptographically weak 512 bit encryption keys.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Logjam is a security exploit discovered in May 2015 that exploits the option of using legacy "export-grade" 512-bit Diffie–Hellman groups dating back to the 1990s.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] It forces susceptible servers to downgrade to cryptographically weak 512-bit Diffie–Hellman groups.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] An attacker can then deduce the keys the client and server determine using the Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The DROWN attack is an exploit that attacks servers supporting contemporary SSL/TLS protocol suites by exploiting their support for the obsolete, insecure, SSLv2 protocol to leverage an attack on connections using up-to-date protocols that would otherwise be secure.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] DROWN exploits a vulnerability in the protocols used and the configuration of the server, rather than any specific implementation error.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Full details of DROWN were announced in March 2016, together with a patch for the exploit.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] At that time, more than 81,000 of the top 1 million most popular websites were among the TLS protected websites that were vulnerable to the DROWN attack.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Practical exploits had not been previously demonstrated for this vulnerability, which was originally discovered by Phillip Rogaway in 2002.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The vulnerability of the attack had been fixed with TLS 1.1 in 2006, but TLS 1.1 had not seen wide adoption prior to this attack demonstration.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] RC4 as a stream cipher is immune to BEAST attack.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Therefore, RC4 was widely used as a way to mitigate BEAST attack on the server side.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] However, in 2013, researchers found more weaknesses in RC4.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Thereafter enabling RC4 on server side was no longer recommended.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Chrome and Firefox themselves are not vulnerable to BEAST attack, however, Mozilla updated their NSS libraries to mitigate BEAST-like attacks.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] NSS is used by Mozilla Firefox and Google Chrome to implement SSL.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Some web servers that have a broken implementation of the SSL specification may stop working as a result.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Microsoft released Security Bulletin MS12-006 on January 10, 2012, which fixed the BEAST vulnerability by changing the way that the Windows Secure Channel (Schannel) component transmits encrypted network packets from the server end.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Users of Internet Explorer (prior to version 11) that run on older versions of Windows (Windows 7, Windows 8 and Windows Server 2008 R2) can restrict use of TLS to 1.1 or higher.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Apple mitigated the BEAST vulnerability by implementing a 1/n-1 split and turning it on by default in OS X Mavericks, released on October 22, 2013.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The authors of the BEAST attack are also the creators of the later CRIME attack, which can allow an attacker to recover the content of web cookies when data compression is used along with TLS.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] When used to recover the content of secret authentication cookies, it allows an attacker to perform session hijacking on an authenticated web session.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The CRIME exploit against HTTP compression has not been mitigated at all, even though the authors of CRIME have warned that this vulnerability might be even more widespread than SPDY and TLS compression combined.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2013 a new instance of the CRIME attack against HTTP compression, dubbed BREACH, was announced.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] All versions of TLS and SSL are at risk from BREACH regardless of the encryption algorithm or cipher used.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a known limitation of TLS as it is susceptible to chosen-plaintext attack against the application-layer data it was meant to protect.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Earlier TLS versions were vulnerable against the padding oracle attack discovered in 2002.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] A novel variant, called the Lucky Thirteen attack, was published in 2013.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Some experts also recommended avoiding triple DES CBC.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] A fix was released in 2014 as the Encrypt-then-MAC extension to the TLS specification.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The Lucky Thirteen attack can be mitigated in TLS 1.2 by using only AES_GCM ciphers; AES_CBC remains vulnerable.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] SSL may safeguard email, VoIP, and other types of communications over insecure networks in addition to its primary use case of secure data transmission between a client and the server.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] On October 14, 2014, Google researchers published a vulnerability in the design of SSL 3.0, which makes CBC mode of operation with SSL 3.0 vulnerable to a padding attack (CVE-2014-3566).
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] They named this attack **POODLE** (**Padding Oracle On Downgraded Legacy Encryption**).
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] On average, attackers only need to make 256 SSL 3.0 requests to reveal one byte of encrypted messages.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Therefore, the man-in-the-middle can first conduct a version rollback attack and then exploit this vulnerability.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] On December 8, 2014, a variant of POODLE was announced that impacts TLS implementations that do not properly enforce padding byte requirements.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Despite the existence of attacks on RC4 that broke its security, cipher suites in SSL and TLS that were based on RC4 were still considered secure prior to 2013 based on the way in which they were used in SSL and TLS.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2011, the RC4 suite was actually recommended as a workaround for the BEAST attack.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] New forms of attack disclosed in March 2013 conclusively demonstrated the feasibility of breaking RC4 in TLS, suggesting it was not a good workaround for BEAST.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] An attack scenario was proposed by AlFardan, Bernstein, Paterson, Poettering and Schuldt that used newly discovered statistical biases in the RC4 key table to recover parts of the plaintext with a large number of TLS encryptions.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] An attack on RC4 in TLS and SSL that requires 13 × 220 encryptions to break RC4 was unveiled on 8 July 2013 and later described as "feasible" in the accompanying presentation at a USENIX Security Symposium in August 2013.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] In July 2015, subsequent improvements in the attack make it increasingly practical to defeat the security of RC4-encrypted TLS.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] As many modern browsers have been designed to defeat BEAST attacks (except Safari for Mac OS X 10.7 or earlier, for iOS 6 or earlier, and for Windows; see § Web browsers), RC4 is no longer a good choice for TLS 1.0.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The CBC ciphers which were affected by the BEAST attack in the past have become a more popular choice for protection.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Mozilla and Microsoft recommend disabling RC4 where possible.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, the use of RC4 cipher suites was officially prohibited in all versions of TLS.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] On September 1, 2015, Microsoft, Google, and Mozilla announced that RC4 cipher suites would be disabled by default in their browsers (Microsoft Edge [Legacy], Internet Explorer 11 on Windows 7/8.1/10, Firefox, and Chrome) in early 2016.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] A TLS (logout) truncation attack blocks a victim's account logout requests so that the user unknowingly remains logged into a web service.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] When the request to sign out is sent, the attacker injects an unencrypted TCP FIN message (no more data from sender) to close the connection.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The server therefore does not receive the logout request and is unaware of the abnormal termination.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The attack does not rely on installing malware on the victim's computer; attackers need only place themselves between the victim and the web server (e.g., by setting up a rogue wireless hotspot).
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] This vulnerability also requires access to the victim's computer.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Another possibility is when using FTP the data connection can have a false FIN in the data stream, and if the protocol rules for exchanging close_notify alerts is not adhered to a file can be truncated.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2013 two researchers from Royal Holloway, University of London discovered a timing attack which allowed them to recover (parts of the) plaintext from a DTLS connection using the OpenSSL or GnuTLS implementation of DTLS when Cipher Block Chaining mode encryption was used.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] This attack, discovered in mid-2016, exploits weaknesses in the Web Proxy Autodiscovery Protocol (WPAD) to expose the URL that a web user is attempting to reach via a TLS-enabled web link.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Disclosure of a URL can violate a user's privacy, not only because of the website accessed, but also because URLs are sometimes used to authenticate users.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Document sharing services, such as those offered by Google and Dropbox, also work by sending a user a security token that is included in the URL.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] An attacker who obtains such URLs may be able to gain full access to a victim's account or data.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The exploit works against almost all browsers and operating systems.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The Sweet32 attack breaks all 64-bit block ciphers used in CBC mode as used in TLS by exploiting a birthday attack and either a man-in-the-middle attack or injection of a malicious JavaScript into a web page.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The purpose of the man-in-the-middle attack or the JavaScript injection is to allow the attacker to capture enough traffic to mount a birthday attack.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The Heartbleed bug is a serious vulnerability specific to the implementation of SSL/TLS in the popular OpenSSL cryptographic software library, affecting versions 1.0.1 to 1.0.1f.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] This weakness, reported in April 2014, allows attackers to extract private keys from servers that should normally be protected.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The Heartbleed bug allows anyone on the Internet to read the memory of the systems protected by the vulnerable versions of the OpenSSL software.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] This compromises the secret private keys associated with the public certificates used to identify the service providers and to encrypt the traffic, the names and passwords of the users and the actual content.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] This allows attackers to eavesdrop on communications, extract data directly from the services and users and to impersonate services and users.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The vulnerability is caused by a buffer over-read bug in the OpenSSL software, rather than a defect in the SSL or TLS protocol specification.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] In September 2014, a variant of Daniel Bleichenbacher's PKCS#1 v1.5 RSA Signature Forgery vulnerability was announced by Intel Security Advanced Threat Research.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] This attack, dubbed BERserk, is a result of incomplete ASN.1 length decoding of public key signatures in some SSL implementations, and allows a man-in-the-middle attack by forging a public key signature.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, after media reported the hidden pre-installation of superfish adware on some Lenovo notebooks, a researcher found a trusted root certificate on affected Lenovo machines to be insecure, as the keys could easily be accessed using the company name, Komodia, as a passphrase.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The Komodia library was designed to intercept client-side TLS/SSL traffic for parental control and surveillance, but it was also used in numerous adware programs, including Superfish, that were often surreptitiously installed unbeknownst to the computer user.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] In turn, these potentially unwanted programs installed the corrupt root certificate, allowing attackers to completely control web traffic and confirm false websites as authentic.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] In May 2016, it was reported that dozens of Danish HTTPS-protected websites belonging to Visa Inc. were vulnerable to attacks allowing hackers to inject malicious code and forged content into the browsers of visitors.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The attacks worked because the TLS implementation used on the affected servers incorrectly reused random numbers (nonces) that are intended to be used only once, ensuring that each TLS handshake is unique.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2017, an implementation error caused by a single mistyped character in code used to parse HTML created a buffer overflow error on Cloudflare servers.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Similar in its effects to the Heartbleed bug discovered in 2014, this overflow error, widely known as Cloudbleed, allowed unauthorized third parties to read data in the memory of programs running on the servers—data that should otherwise have been protected by TLS.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] As of June 2025, the Trustworthy Internet Movement estimated the ratio of websites that are vulnerable to TLS attacks.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Forward secrecy is a property of cryptographic systems which ensures that a session key derived from a set of public and private keys will not be compromised if one of the private keys is compromised in the future.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] An implementation of TLS can provide forward secrecy by requiring the use of ephemeral Diffie–Hellman key exchange to establish session keys, and some notable TLS implementations do so exclusively: e.g., Gmail and other Google HTTPS services that use OpenSSL.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] However, many clients and servers supporting TLS (including browsers and web servers) are not configured to implement such restrictions.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] In practice, unless a web service uses Diffie–Hellman key exchange to implement forward secrecy, all of the encrypted web traffic to and from that service can be decrypted by a third party if it obtains the server's master (private) key; e.g., by means of a court order.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Even where Diffie–Hellman key exchange is implemented, server-side session management mechanisms can impact forward secrecy.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The use of TLS session tickets (a TLS extension) causes the session to be protected by AES128-CBC-SHA256 regardless of any other negotiated TLS parameters, including forward secrecy ciphersuites, and the long-lived TLS session ticket keys defeat the attempt to implement forward secrecy.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Stanford University research in 2014 also found that of 473,802 TLS servers surveyed, 82.9% of the servers deploying ephemeral Diffie–Hellman (DHE) key exchange to support forward secrecy were using weak Diffie–Hellman parameters.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] These weak parameter choices could potentially compromise the effectiveness of the forward secrecy that the servers sought to provide.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Since late 2011, Google has provided forward secrecy with TLS by default to users of its Gmail service, along with Google Docs and encrypted search, among other services.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Since November 2013, Twitter has provided forward secrecy with TLS to users of its service.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] As of August 2019, about 80% of TLS-enabled websites are configured to use cipher suites that provide forward secrecy to most web browsers.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS interception (or HTTPS interception if applied particularly to that protocol) is the practice of intercepting an encrypted data stream in order to decrypt it, read and possibly manipulate it, and then re-encrypt it and send the data on its way again.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] This is done by way of a "transparent proxy": the interception software terminates the incoming TLS connection, inspects the HTTP plaintext, and then creates a new TLS connection to the destination.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS/HTTPS interception is used as an information security measure by network operators in order to be able to scan for and protect against the intrusion of malicious content into the network, such as computer viruses and other malware.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Such content could otherwise not be detected as long as it is protected by encryption, which is increasingly the case as a result of the routine use of HTTPS and other secure protocols.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] A significant drawback of TLS/HTTPS interception is that it introduces new security risks of its own.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] One notable limitation is that it provides a point where network traffic is available unencrypted thus giving attackers an incentive to attack this point in particular in order to gain access to otherwise secure content.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The interception also allows the network operator, or persons who gain access to its interception system, to perform man-in-the-middle attacks against network users.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] A 2017 study found that "HTTPS interception has become startlingly widespread, and that interception products as a class have a dramatically negative impact on connection security".
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The TLS protocol exchanges *records*, which encapsulate the data to be exchanged in a specific format (see below).
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Each record can be compressed, padded, appended with a message authentication code (MAC), or encrypted, all depending on the state of the connection.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Each record has a *content type* field that designates the type of data encapsulated, a length field and a TLS version field.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The data encapsulated may be control or procedural messages of the TLS itself, or simply the application data needed to be transferred by TLS.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The specifications (cipher suite, keys etc.) required to exchange application data by TLS, are agreed upon in the "TLS handshake" between the client requesting the data and the server responding to requests.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The protocol therefore defines both the structure of payloads transferred in TLS and the procedure to establish and monitor the transfer.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] When the connection starts, the record encapsulates a "control" protocol – the handshake messaging protocol (*content type* 22).
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] This protocol is used to exchange all the information required by both sides for the exchange of the actual application data by TLS.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] It defines the format of messages and the order of their exchange.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] These may vary according to the demands of the client and server – i.e., there are several possible procedures to set up the connection.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] This initial exchange results in a successful TLS connection (both parties ready to transfer application data with TLS) or an alert message (as specified below).
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Application phase: at this point, the "handshake" is complete and the application protocol is enabled, with content type of 23.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Application messages exchanged between client and server will also be authenticated and optionally encrypted exactly like in their *Finished* message.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Otherwise, the content type will return 25 and the client will not authenticate.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The following *full* example shows a client being authenticated (in addition to the server as in the example above; see mutual authentication) via TLS using certificates exchanged between both peers.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The client now sends a **ChangeCipherSpec** record, essentially telling the server, "Everything I tell you from now on will be authenticated (and encrypted if encryption was negotiated).
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] "The ChangeCipherSpec is itself a record-level protocol and has type 20 and not 22.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Application messages exchanged between client and server will also be encrypted exactly like in their *Finished* message.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Public key operations (e.g., RSA) are relatively expensive in terms of computational power.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS provides a secure shortcut in the handshake mechanism to avoid these operations: resumed sessions.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Resumed sessions are implemented using session IDs or session tickets.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Apart from the performance benefit, resumed sessions can also be used for single sign-on, as it guarantees that both the original session and any resumed session originate from the same client.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] This is of particular importance for the FTP over TLS/SSL protocol, which would otherwise suffer from a man-in-the-middle attack in which an attacker could intercept the contents of the secondary data connections.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The TLS 1.3 handshake was condensed to only one round trip compared to the two round trips required in previous versions of TLS/SSL.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] To start the handshake, the client guesses which key exchange algorithm will be selected by the server and sends a **ClientHello** message to the server containing a list of supported ciphers (in order of the client's preference) and public keys for some or all of its key exchange guesses.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] If the client successfully guesses the key exchange algorithm, 1 round trip is eliminated from the handshake.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] After receiving the **ClientHello**, the server selects a cipher and sends back a **ServerHello** with its own public key, followed by server **Certificate** and **Finished** messages.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] After the client receives the server's finished message, it now is coordinated with the server on which cipher suite to use.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] In an ordinary *full* handshake, the server sends a *session id* as part of the **ServerHello** message.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The client associates this *session id* with the server's IP address and TCP port, so that when the client connects again to that server, it can use the *session id* to shortcut the handshake.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] In the server, the *session id* maps to the cryptographic parameters previously negotiated, specifically the "master secret".
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Both sides must have the same "master secret" or the resumed handshake will fail (this prevents an eavesdropper from using a *session id*).
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The random data in the **ClientHello** and **ServerHello** messages virtually guarantee that the generated connection keys will be different from in the previous connection.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] In the RFCs, this type of handshake is called an *abbreviated* handshake.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] It is also described in the literature as a *restart* handshake.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The server now sends a **ChangeCipherSpec** record, essentially telling the client, "Everything I tell you from now on will be encrypted." The ChangeCipherSpec is itself a record-level protocol and has type 20 and not 22.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Instead of session IDs, TLS can also be extended via use of session tickets.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] It defines a way to resume a TLS session without requiring that session-specific state is stored at the TLS server.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] When using session tickets, the TLS server stores its session-specific state in a session ticket and sends the session ticket to the TLS client for storing.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The client resumes a TLS session by sending the session ticket to the server, and the server resumes the TLS session according to the session-specific state in the ticket.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The session ticket is encrypted and authenticated by the server, and the server verifies its validity before using its contents.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] One particular weakness of this method with OpenSSL is that it always limits encryption and authentication security of the transmitted TLS session ticket to `AES128-CBC-SHA256`, no matter what other TLS parameters were negotiated for the actual TLS session.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] This means that the state information (the TLS session ticket) is not as well protected as the TLS session itself.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] This is the general format of all TLS records.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the Record Layer Protocol Type contained in this record.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the major and minor version of TLS prior to TLS 1.3 for the contained message.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] and application must send supported versions in an extra message extension block.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] One or more messages identified by the Protocol field.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Note that this field may be encrypted depending on the state of the connection.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] field, with additional key material included.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Most messages exchanged during the setup of the TLS session are based on this record, unless an error or warning occurs and needs to be signaled by an Alert protocol record (see below), or the encryption mode of the session is modified by another record (see **ChangeCipherSpec** protocol below).
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the handshake message type.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a 3-byte field indicating the length of the handshake data, not including the header.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Note that multiple handshake messages may be combined within one record.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] This record should normally not be sent during normal handshaking or application exchanges.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] However, this message can be sent at any time during the handshake and up to the closure of the session.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] If this is used to signal a fatal error, the session will be closed immediately after sending this record, so this record is used to give a reason for this closure.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] If the alert level is flagged as a warning, the remote can decide to close the session if it decides that the session is not reliable enough for its needs (before doing so, the remote may also send its own signal).
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The length of the rest of fields, which is 2.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the level of alert.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] If the level is fatal, the sender should close the session immediately.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Otherwise, the recipient may decide to terminate the session itself, by sending its own fatal alert and closing the session itself immediately after sending it.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The use of Alert records is optional, however if it is missing before the session closure, the session may be resumed automatically (with its handshakes).
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Alert type (with a simple warning level) to prevent such automatic resume of a new session.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies which type of alert is being sent.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The length of the rest of fields, which is 1.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the CCS Protocol type.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] The last byte contains the padding length.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] From the application protocol point of view, TLS belongs to a lower layer, although the TCP/IP model is too coarse to show it.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] This means that the TLS handshake is usually (except in the STARTTLS case) performed before the application protocol can start.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] In the name-based virtual server feature being provided by the application layer, all co-hosted virtual servers share the same certificate because the server has to select and send a certificate immediately after the ClientHello message.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a big problem in hosting environments because it means either sharing the same certificate among all customers or using a different IP address for each of them.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] To provide the server name, Transport Layer Security (TLS) Extensions allow clients to include a Server Name Indication extension (SNI) in the extended ClientHello message.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] This extension hints to the server immediately which name the client wishes to connect to, so the server can select the appropriate certificate to send to the clients.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] There is also a method to implement name-based virtual hosting by upgrading HTTP to TLS via an HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] Normally this is to securely implement HTTP over TLS within the main "http" URI scheme instead of the commonly used "https" scheme.
[src:reqwest-rust/transport-layer-security-p02] This would avoid forking the URI space and reduces the number of used ports, however, few implementations currently support this.
[src:reqwest-rust/url] A **uniform resource locator** (**URL**), colloquially known as a **web address**, is a reference to a resource on the World Wide Web.
[src:reqwest-rust/url] A URL specifies the location of a resource on a computer network and a mechanism for retrieving it.
[src:reqwest-rust/url] A URL is a specific type of Uniform Resource Identifier (URI), although many people use the two terms interchangeably.
[src:reqwest-rust/url] A URL is most commonly used to reference a web page (HTTP/HTTPS) but is also used for file transfer (FTP), email (mailto), database access (JDBC), and many other applications.
[src:reqwest-rust/url] Most web browsers display the URL of a web page above the page in an address bar.
[src:reqwest-rust/url] As an example of a web page URL, `https://www.example.com/index.html` indicates protocol `https`, hostname `www.example.com`, and file name `index.html`.
[src:reqwest-rust/url] The Uniform Resource Locator was defined in RFC 1738 in 1994 by Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, and the URI working group of the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF), as an outcome of collaboration started at the IETF Living Documents birds of a feather session in 1992.
[src:reqwest-rust/url] The format combines the pre-existing system of domain names (created in 1985) with file path syntax, where slashes are used to separate directory and filenames.
[src:reqwest-rust/url] Conventions already existed where server names could be prefixed to complete file paths, preceded by a double slash (`//`).
[src:reqwest-rust/url] Berners-Lee later expressed regret at the use of dots to separate the parts of the domain name within URIs, wishing he had used slashes throughout, and also said that, given the colon following the first component of a URI, the two slashes before the domain name were unnecessary.
[src:reqwest-rust/url] Early WorldWideWeb collaborators, including Berners-Lee, originally proposed the use of UDIs: Universal Document Identifiers.
[src:reqwest-rust/url] An early (1993) draft of the HTML Specification referred to "Universal" Resource Locators.
[src:reqwest-rust/url] This was dropped some time between June 1994 and October 1994.
[src:reqwest-rust/url] In his book *Weaving the Web*, Berners-Lee emphasizes his preference for the original inclusion of "universal" in the expansion rather than the word "uniform", to which it was later changed, and he gives a brief account of the contention that led to the change.
[src:reqwest-rust/url] Every HTTP URL conforms to the syntax of a generic URI.
[src:reqwest-rust/url] A component is *undefined* if it has an associated delimiter and the delimiter does not appear in the URI; the scheme and path components are always defined.
[src:reqwest-rust/url] A component is *empty* if it has no characters; the scheme component is always non-empty.
[src:reqwest-rust/url] A web browser will usually dereference a URL by performing an HTTP request to the specified host, by default on port number 80.
[src:reqwest-rust/url] URLs using the `https` scheme require that requests and responses be made over a secure connection to the website.
[src:reqwest-rust/url] Internet users are distributed throughout the world using a wide variety of languages and alphabets, and expect to be able to create URLs in their own local alphabets.
[src:reqwest-rust/url] An Internationalized Resource Identifier (IRI) is a form of URL that includes Unicode characters.
[src:reqwest-rust/url] The parts of the URL requiring special treatment for different alphabets are the domain name and path.
[src:reqwest-rust/url] The domain name in the IRI is known as an Internationalized Domain Name (IDN).
[src:reqwest-rust/url] Web and Internet software automatically convert the domain name into punycode usable by the Domain Name System; for example, the Chinese URL `http://例子.卷筒纸` becomes `http://xn--fsqu00a.xn--3lr804guic/`.
[src:reqwest-rust/url] The `xn--` indicates that the character was not originally ASCII.
[src:reqwest-rust/url] The URL path name can also be specified by the user in the local writing system.
[src:reqwest-rust/url] If not already encoded, it is converted to UTF-8, and any characters not part of the basic URL character set are escaped as hexadecimal using percent-encoding; for example, the Japanese URL `http://example.com/引き割り.html` becomes `http://example.com/%E5%BC%95%E3%81%8D%E5%89%B2%E3%82%8A.html`.
[src:reqwest-rust/url] The target computer decodes the address and displays the page.
[src:reqwest-rust/url] Protocol-relative links (PRL), also known as protocol-relative URLs (PRURL), are URLs that have no protocol specified.
[src:reqwest-rust/url] For example, `//example.com` will use the protocol of the current page, typically HTTP or HTTPS.
